'''Derrick Burckley Etienne Jr.''' (born 25 November 1996) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for [[Toronto FC]] in [[Major League Soccer]]. Born in the United States, he plays for the [[Haiti national football team|Haiti national team]].

Born in Richmond, Virginia, and raised in [[Paterson, New Jersey]], Etienne is the son of former Haitian International and [[Long Island Rough Riders]] forward [[Derrick Etienne (footballer, born 1974)|Derrick Etienne]] and the older brother of Haitian International midfielder [[Danielle Etienne]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-soccer/mtt/derrick_etienne_974774.html|title=Derrick Etienne Bio – VirginiaSports.com – University of Virginia Official Athletics Website – UVA Cavaliers Men's Soccer|access-date=10 September 2015|archive-date=21 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171021163527/http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-soccer/mtt/derrick_etienne_974774.html|url-status=dead}}</ref>

==Early career==

===High school===
Etienne was born in [[Virginia]] (where his father Derrick Sr. played for the [[Richmond Kickers]]) before moving to [[Paterson, New Jersey]] where he spent his childhood.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/12/21/new-york-red-bulls-sign-brandon-allen-derrick-etienne-homegrown-players|title=New York Red Bulls sign Brandon Allen, Derrick Etienne as Homegrown Players, now lead MLS with 7 HGPs|author=Staff|website=[[Major League Soccer]]|date=21 December 2015|access-date=21 March 2016|quote=Etienne, from Paterson, New Jersey, joined the Red Bulls academy as an Under-14 player and advanced through the developmental system.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/teams/redbulls2.php?article_id=44819 |title=Hoping For More Back From Training With Haiti's Copa Team, Etienne Jr. Could Get To Play in Friendlies This Summer |editor=Dyer, Kristian R. |date=2 June 2016 |publisher=Big Apple Soccer |access-date=14 June 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610204902/http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/teams/redbulls2.php?article_id=44819 |archive-date=10 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He attended high school at [[Passaic County Technical Institute]] in [[Wayne, New Jersey]], playing varsity soccer for the Bulldogs in his freshman year with 6 goals and 9 assists.{{citation needed|date=July 2020}} He helped lead the team to the state Vo-Tech tournament and the [[Big North Conference (New Jersey)|Big North Conference]] Liberty division titles. Etienne ended his high school playing career to focus on the Red Bulls Academy following the season.

===College career===
Etienne spent his youth club career with the [[New York Red Bulls]] Academy. Etienne joined the academy in 2009 at the U-14 level at age 12. While being one of the youngest players on the team, Etienne progressed and stood out at the U14, U15, U16, and U18 levels before signing a letter of intent to play college soccer at the [[University of Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Virginia Welcomes Six Student-Athletes for 2015–16 School Year|url=http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-soccer/spec-rel/021815aaa.html|website=VirginiaSports.com|publisher=Virginia Sports|access-date=10 September 2015|date=18 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 2014 Youth All-America Teams|url = http://www.nscaa.com/news/2014/11/2014-youth-all-america-teams|website = www.nscaa.com|access-date = 9 November 2015}}</ref> Despite appearing for NYRB II, Etienne was able to maintain his college eligibility and on 29 August 2015, he made his collegiate debut for the Cavaliers in a 1–0 victory over [[UNC Charlotte 49ers men's soccer|UNC Charlotte]].<ref>{{cite web|title=No. 2 Virginia Downs No. 17 Charlotte in Season Opener, 1–0|url=http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/082915aaa.html|website=VirginiaSports.com|publisher=Virginia Sports|access-date=10 September 2015|date=29 August 2015}}</ref> On 21 September 2015, Etienne scored his first collegiate goal in a 1–0 victory over his father's alma mater, [[VCU Rams men's soccer|VCU]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Late Etienne Goal Lifts No. 6 Virginia to 1–0 Win at VCU|url = http://www.virginiasports.com/sports/m-soccer/recaps/092115aaa.html|website = www.virginiasports.com|access-date = 10 November 2015}}</ref> Later that same year, Etienne chose not to complete his degree at Virginia, and signed a pro contract.

==Professional==
===New York Red Bulls===
On 28 March 2015, Etienne made his professional debut for [[United Soccer League|USL]] affiliate club [[New York Red Bulls II]] in a 0–0 draw against the [[Rochester Rhinos]].<ref>{{cite web|title=MATCH RECAP: Red Bulls II 0, Rochester Rhinos, 0|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2015/03/28/match-recap-red-bulls-ii-0-rochester-rhinos-0|website=newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls Communications|access-date=10 September 2015|date=28 March 2015}}</ref> On 24 May 2015 Etienne scored his first professional goal and assisted on another, helping New York to a 3–2 victory over [[FC Montreal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/news/2015/05/usl-match-recap-red-bulls-ii-3-fc-montreal-2|title= Derrick Etienne earns Man of the Match honors after goal and assist|website=newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls|date=24 May 2015|access-date=24 May 2015}}</ref> For this performance Etienne was named to the USL team of the Week.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2015/05/26/derrick-etienne-named-usl-team-week |title= MATCH RECAP: Etienne named to USL Team of the Week |website=newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls|date=26 May 2015 |access-date=26 May 2015}}</ref> On 30 May 2015 Etienne scored his second professional goal for New York in a 4–2 loss to his father's former club, [[Richmond Kickers]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = The best goals of the week: Lionel Messi, Sophie Schmidt and Ruslan Rotan|url = https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/jun/01/best-goals-week-lionel-messi-barcelona-ruslan-rotan|website =[[The Guardian]]|date= 1 June 2015|access-date= 10 November 2015|first = Paul|last = Campbell}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = NYRB II Fall, 4–2, at Richmond – OurSports Central|url = http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=4979419|website = www.oursportscentral.com|date = 31 May 2015|publisher = Our Sports Central Today|access-date = 10 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Kickers Host NY Red Bulls II Saturday |url = https://www.richmondkickers.com/home/879693.html|website=richmondkickers.com|publisher=Richmond Kickers|date=28 May 2015|access-date=10 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040713/https://www.richmondkickers.com/home/879693.html|archive-date=4 March 2016}}</ref> On 20 June 2015 Etienne scored for New York in a 2–0 victory over [[Louisville City FC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2015/06/20/match-recap-new-york-red-bulls-ii-2-louisville-city-fc-o |title= Match Recap: New York Red Bulls II 2, Louisville City FC O |website= newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls|date=20 June 2015|access-date=20 June 2015}}</ref>

On 21 December 2015, Etienne signed a [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|Homegrown Contract]] with the [[New York Red Bulls]], forgoing his remaining NCAA eligibility.<ref>{{cite web|title=New York Red Bulls sign Allen and Etienne|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/12/21/new-york-red-bulls-sign-brandon-allen-derrick-etienne-homegrown-players|website=mlssoccer.com|publisher=Major League Soccer|date=21 December 2015|access-date=21 December 2015}}</ref> Etienne was loaned back to Red Bulls II in 2016 for their home opener on 26 March.<ref name="New York Red Bulls Loan Seven Players to NYRB II">{{cite web|title=New York Red Bulls Loan Seven Players to NYRB II|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2016/03/26/new-york-red-bulls-loan-seven-players-nyrb-ii|website=newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls|date=26 March 2016|access-date=26 March 2016}}</ref> On 10 April 2016 Etienne scored his first goal of the season, helping [[New York Red Bulls II]] to a 4–0 victory over [[Bethlehem Steel FC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/635490?referrer_id=2333971|title=Etienne Brings Everything Together |website=uslsoccer.com |publisher=United Soccer League|date=11 April 2016|access-date=11 May 2020}}</ref> On 7 May 2016 Etienne scored his second goal of the season in 3–1 victory over [[Pittsburgh Riverhounds SC|Pittsburgh Riverhounds]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2016/05/07/usl-match-recap-pittsburgh-riverhounds-1-new-york-red-bulls-ii-3|title= USL Match Recap: Pittsburgh 1 NYRB II 3|website= newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls|date=7 May 2016 |access-date=7 May 2016}}</ref> On 23 October 2016 Etienne opened the scoring for New York and also recorded an assist in a 5–1 victory over [[Swope Park Rangers]] in the [[2016 USL Playoffs|2016 USL Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/712570?referrer_id=2333971|title=Allen's Hat Trick Leads Red Bulls II to USL Cup |website=uslsoccer.com|publisher=United Soccer League|date=23 October 2016|access-date=23 October 2016}}</ref>

On 28 May 2017, Etienne scored his first goal of the season for [[New York Red Bulls II]], scoring the game winner on a free kick in a 2–1 victory over [[Charleston Battery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2017/05/28/usl-match-recap-second-half-surge-sees-nyrb-ii-edge-charleston|title=USL Match Recap: Second Half Surge Sees NYRB II Edge Charleston|website=newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls|date=28 May 2017|access-date=28 May 2017}}</ref> On 19 July 2017, Etienne recorded his first assist for the first team finding [[Daniel Royer]] as he scored New York's fourth goal of the day in a 5–1 victory over [[San Jose Earthquakes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2017/07/19/new-york-red-bulls-5-san-jose-earthquakes-1-2017-mls-match-recap|title=New York Red Bulls 5, San Jose Earthquakes 1 – 2017 MLS Match Recap |website=mlssoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer|date=19 July 2017|access-date=11 May 2020}}</ref>

On 31 March 2018 Etienne scored his first goal for the [[New York Red Bulls]] in a 4–3 loss to [[Orlando City SC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2018-03-31-orlando-city-sc-vs-new-york-red-bulls/recap|title=Orlando City SC 4, New York Red Bulls 3 2018 MLS Match Recap|date=31 March 2018|website=mlssoccer.com|publisher=Major League Soccer|language=en|access-date=31 March 2018}}</ref> On 5 May 2018, Etienne scored the last goal for New York in a 4–0 derby victory over [[New York City FC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2018/05/05/postgame-notes-red-bulls-roll-past-rival-nycfc-4-0|title=Red Bulls Roll Past Rival NYCFC, 4–0|date=5 May 2018|website=newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls|language=en|access-date=5 May 2018}}</ref> The following week, on 12 May Etienne scored New York's second goal in a 2–1 victory over [[Colorado Rapids]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2018/05/13/final-plays-difference-third-straight-win|title=Final Plays the Difference in Third-Straight Win|date=13 May 2018|website=newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls|language=en|access-date=13 May 2018}}</ref> On 28 October 2018, Etienne scored the game-winning goal as the Red Bulls clinched their third [[Supporters Shield]] in a 1–0 win over [[Orlando City SC]].

On 8 August 2019, Etienne was loaned to MLS side [[FC Cincinnati]] for the remainder of the 2019 season, where he scored zero goals in five appearances.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fccincinnati.com/post/2019/08/08/derrick-etienne-jr-acquired-loan|title=Derrick Etienne Jr. acquired on loan|website=fccincinnati.com| publisher=FC Cincinnati|date=8 August 2019|access-date=11 May 2020}}</ref>

Etienne was released by New York at the end of their 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorkredbulls.com/post/2019/11/21/new-york-red-bulls-announce-end-year-roster-decisions|title=New York Red Bulls Announce End of Year Roster Decisions|website=newyorkredbulls.com|publisher=New York Red Bulls|date=21 November 2019|access-date=11 May 2020}}</ref>

===Columbus Crew===
Following his release from New York Red Bulls, Etienne moved to [[Columbus Crew]] on 4 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbuscrewsc.com/post/2020/02/04/columbus-crew-sc-signs-midfielder-derrick-etienne-jr|title=SIGNED &#124; Columbus Crew SC signs midfielder Derrick Etienne Jr.|website=columbuscrewsc.com|publisher=Columbus Crew SC|date=4 February 2020|access-date=11 May 2020}}</ref> He scored the second goal in the Crew's 3–0 victory over [[Seattle Sounders FC]] in [[MLS Cup 2020]], which saw the club win their second league championship.  On 26 October 2022, Columbus Crew released Etienne, making him a free agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.columbuscrew.com/news/columbus-crew-announces-end-of-2022-roster-decisions|title=Columbus Crew announces end-of-2022 roster decisions|website=columbuscrew.com|date=26 October 2022}}</ref>

===Atlanta United FC===
On 30 November 2022, [[Atlanta United FC]] announced that they signed Etienne to a contract through 2025, with options for 2026 and 2027.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atlutd.com/news/atlanta-united-signs-free-agent-midfielder-derrick-etienne-jr|title=Atlanta United signs free agent midfielder Derrick Etienne Jr.|website=atlutd.com|date=30 November 2022}}</ref>

==International career==
Though born and raised in the United States, Etienne chose to represent [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]] in international competition, becoming the third member of his family to do so after his father and uncle. He was a member of the Haiti Under-17 team that competed in the [[2013 CONCACAF U-17 Championship]] in Panama as well as the Haiti Under-20 team that competed in the [[2015 CONCACAF U-20 Championship]] in Jamaica.

On 9 November 2016, he made his first senior team appearance for Haiti, coming on as a substitute in a 5–2 loss to [[French Guiana national football team|French Guiana]] in the third round of [[2017 Caribbean Cup qualification]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/teams/redbulls2.php?article_id=46444|title=MAKING HIS DEBUT: Etienne, Jr. plays for Haiti for the first time|date=9 November 2016|access-date=10 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111061741/http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/teams/redbulls2.php?article_id=46444|archive-date=11 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He scored his first international goal on 8 January 2017 against [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]] in the 2017 Caribbean Cup qualification fifth place playoff.

In the summer of 2019, Etienne competed in the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup]] helping Haiti win Group B after defeating Bermuda, Nicaragua, and Costa Rica to advance to the knockout stage. After upsetting Canada 3–2 in the quarter-final match, Haiti advanced to the semifinals of the Gold Cup for the first time in national team history but fell short in a 1–0 loss to Mexico after extra time.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Newport|first=Kyle|title=Haiti Advances to 2019 Gold Cup Semifinals with 3-2 Win vs. Canada|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2843439-haiti-advances-to-2019-gold-cup-semifinals-with-3-2-win-vs-canada|access-date=15 August 2020|website=Bleacher Report|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Armstrong|first=Megan|title=Controversial Penalty Sends Mexico to 2019 Gold Cup Final with Win vs. Haiti|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2843992-controversial-penalty-sends-mexico-to-2019-gold-cup-final-with-win-vs-haiti|access-date=15 August 2020|website=Bleacher Report|language=en}}</ref>

